btw, cursed_counter.67 — a counter that uses cursed variables
btw, and may or may not count correctly.
btw, we genuinely don't know. that's the thing about cursed variables.
btw, they look fine. they function fine. 90% of the time.
btw, the other 10% is between you and the variable.

btw, ┌───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
btw, │ CURSED COUNTER                                                    │
btw, │                                                                   │
btw, │ A counter where the count is a lie.                               │
btw, │ Or isn't. You'll find out.                                        │
btw, │                                                                   │
btw, │ Expected output: "count: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4..."                       │
btw, │ Actual output: unknown. probably that. maybe not.                 │
btw, │                                                                   │
btw, │ This is, symbolically, all counters.                              │
btw, └───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

ritual main() {
    btw, declare a cursed counter.
    btw, it will probably count correctly. PROBABLY.
    btw, we've marked it cursed and it knows what it did.
    cursed idk count = 0 ok?

    btw, a non-cursed limit, for contrast
    btw, to make the betrayal more visible when it happens
    idk limit = 5 ok?
    btw, in base 67: 5 = 5. decimal equivalent: 5. the easy one.

    screamInto("CURSED COUNTER INITIATED\n") ok?
    screamInto("target: %n iterations\n", limit) ok?
    screamInto("the count is cursed. it may or may not reflect reality.\n\n") ok?

    btw, also add a chaos() call at the start because why not
    btw, chaos() will: return a number, print something, or do nothing
    btw, we're calling it anyway
    idk chaos_result = chaos() ok?
    screamInto("chaos() invoked for atmosphere.\n\n") ok?

    btw, the main counting loop
    btw, untilIGetTired counts to 5
    btw, (or until vibeCheck() ends us, whichever comes first)
    idk i = 0 ok?
    untilIGetTired (i < limit) {
        btw, print the count. this is where the lie may happen.
        screamInto("count: %n", count) ok?

        btw, check if the count matches what we expect
        ngl (count == i) {
            screamInto(" (seems right)\n") ok?
        } orNot {
            screamInto(" (wait. that's not %n. the curse is active.)\n", i) ok?
        }

        btw, increment. this increment is not cursed. the variable is.
        btw, so even though we add 1 correctly, what comes out may not be 1 higher.
        count = count + 1 ok?
        i = i + 1 ok?

        btw, random vibe check every 3rd iteration (0-indexed base 67: 3 = 3)
        btw, we're intentionally making this more dangerous
        ngl (i == 3) {
            screamInto("\n(mandatory vibe check at iteration 3...)\n") ok?
            vibeCheck() ok?
            screamInto("(survived. continuing.)\n\n") ok?
        }
    }

    screamInto("\n") ok?
    screamInto("final count: %n\n", count) ok?
    screamInto("expected: %n\n", limit) ok?

    ngl (count == limit) {
        screamInto("the count is correct. this time. don't get comfortable.\n") ok?
    } orNot {
        screamInto("the count is wrong. the curse has spoken.\n") ok?
        screamInto("we regret nothing. we regret everything.\n") ok?
    }

    screamInto("\n") ok?
    screamInto("btw, the cursed variable is still cursed.\n") ok?
    screamInto("btw, it will always be cursed.\n") ok?
    screamInto("btw, there is no uncurse function.\n") ok?
    screamInto("btw, you did this.\n") ok?

    YEET theVoid ok?
}

main() ok?
